===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|remembren|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|remembrer||to remember|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|rememorari||to remember again|lang=la}}, from {{term|re-|lang=la}} + {{term|memor||mindful|lang=la}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|(s)mer-|to think about, be mindful, remember|lang=}}. Cognate with {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|mimorian|lang=ang}}, {{term|mymerian||to remember, commemorate|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|mamorian|māmorian|to deliberate, plan out, design|lang=ang}}. More at {{l|en|mammer}}.

{{rel-top|etymology note}}
The success of the [[Old French]] word was aided by its proximity in sound and meaning to an existing {{etyl|gem}} word: {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|mimorian|lang=ang}}, {{term|mymerian|lang=ang}} "to remember, commemorate" from {{proto|Germanic|mimrōjanan||mīmrōjanan|to remember, be mindful|lang=en}}, from the same {{proto|Indo-European}} source, and is akin to {{etyl|frs|-}} ''[[mimerje|mīmerje]]'' "to ponder, reflect", {{etyl|gml|-}} ''[[mimeren|mīmeren, mīmern]]'' "to ponder, meditate", {{etyl|dum|-}} ''[[mimeren#Middle Dutch|mīmeren]]'' "to reflect, think to oneself" ({{etyl|nl|-}} ''[[mijmeren]]'' "to muse, reflect deeply"), [[Old English]] {{term|mimor||mindful|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|non|-}} ''[[Mímir]]'', ''[[Mim]]'', Norse god of Memory, [[Old English]] ''[[mamrian#Old English|māmrian]]'' "to think out, design". Related to {{l|en|mourn}}.

Displaced native {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|ȝemuneȝen|ȝemuneȝen|to remember|lang=enm|sc=Latinx}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|gemynegian|ġemynegian|to remember, remind|lang=ang}}; {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|minnen|minnen|to remember, have in mind|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|minna|minna|to remind|lang=non}}; {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|munden|lang=enm}}, {{term|ȝemunden|ȝemunden|to bear in mind, remember|lang=enm|sc=Latinx}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|gemynd|ġemynd|memory, remembrance|lang=ang}}; {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|ithenchen|lang=enm}}, {{term|ȝethenchen|ȝethenchen|to think on, remember|lang=enm|sc=Latinx}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|geþencan|ġeþencan|lang=ang}}; {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term|manien|manien|to remind, mention, remember|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|manian|manian|to admonish, remind, mention|lang=ang}}.
{{rel-bottom}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To [[recall]] from one's [[memory]]; to have an image in one's memory.
#: ''I '''remember''' the formula.''
#: ''I '''remember''' locking the door.''
#* {{quote-book|1852|Mrs M.A. Thompson|chapter=The Tutor's Daughter|Graham's American Monthly Magazine of Literature, Art, and Fashion|page=266|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=hdcRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA266
|passage=In the lightness of my heart I sang catches of songs as my horse gayly bore me along the well-'''remembered''' road.}}
# To [[memorize]]; to put something into memory.
#: ''Please '''remember''' this formula!''
# To not forget (to do something required)
#: '''''Remember''' to lock the door when you go out.''
# To [[convey]] greetings.
#: ''Please '''remember''' me to your brother.''
# {{obsolete}} To [[put in mind]]; to [[remind]] (also used reflexively)
#* [[:w:Dante Gabriel Rossetti|Dante Gabriel Rossetti]], Secret Parting, lines 5-7
#*: ''But soon, '''remembering her''' how brief the whole
#*: ''Of joy, which its own hours annihilate,
#*: ''Her set gaze gathered
# {{intransitive}} To engage in the process of recalling memories.
#: ''You don't have to remind him, he '''remembers''' very well.''

====Usage notes====
* In sense 1 this is a [[catenative]] verb that takes the ''gerund (-ing)''.
* In sense 3 this is a [[catenative]] verb that takes the ''to'' infinitive.
* See [[Appendix:English catenative verbs]]

